text.tspan: MARS' ATMOSPHERE IS TOO THIN FOR MOST PARACHUTES.
PREVIOUS MISSIONS HAVE USED VERY SPECIAL PARACHUTES
THAT CAN OPEN WHILE THE VEHICLE IS SUPERSONIC; RED DRAGON
CANNOT. THE LANDING IS PERFORMED ENTIRELY UNDER ITS OWN
THE FINS ON THE TRUNK ARE USED ONLY FOR PASSIVE AERODYNAMIC
STABILITY DURING A LAUNCH ABORT; SINCE RED DRAGON HAS NO CREW
ON BOARD, IT DOES NOT NEED ABORT CAPABILITY. THE FINS ARE THEREFORE
REMOVED TO CUT DOWN ON MASS.
THE REPURPOSED CREW DRAGON CAPSULE DOES NOT HAVE LIFE SUPPORT
OR SUPPLIES FOR CREW; EVEN IF IT DID, IT IS A ONE-WAY TRIP. NO CREW
OR LIVING CREATURES WILL BE ONBOARD RED DRAGON.
NEARLY ALL OF THE FUEL IS SPENT SLOWING DOWN FOR LANDING. NO
FUEL REMAINS FOR ANY OTHER PURPOSE AND THE CAPSULE WILL
IN A HOVERSLAM, THE ENGINES ARE THROTTLED ALL THE WAY UP AND
KEPT AT FULL THROTTLE UNTIL TOUCHDOWN. THIS IS THE MOST EFFICIENT
LANDING TECHNIQUE, BUT ALSO REQUIRES PRECISE TIMING TO SUCCEED.
THE SOLAR ARRAY EXTENDS TO THE BACK SIDE OF THE TRUNK; THIS IS TO
PROVIDE ELECTRICITY EVEN WHILE THE SPACECRAFT PERFORMS ITS
BARBECUE ROLL MANEUVER DURING THE JOURNEY TO MARS.
RED DRAGON MISSION LAUNCHES ON FALCON HEAVY
DRAGON FLIPS IN PREPARATION FOR MARS ENTRY
DOWNRANGE BARGE LANDING OF CENTER CORE MAY OCCUR
SECOND STAGE BATTERIES ONLY LAST 90 MINUTES
BOOSTERS RETURN TO LAUNCH SITE FOR REUSE
NOT REQUIRED IF NO CREW ABOARD
RED DRAGON PERFORMS A BARBECUE ROLL TO KEEP COOL
